The app sets no security-related HTTP headers. Defaults expose `X-Powered-By: Express` and omit protections like CSP, HSTS, and `X-Content-Type-Options`.

**Recommendation:** Add `helmet` and disable the Express fingerprint header.
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 2. No rate limiting (OWASP A04: Insecure Design / DoS)
Both endpoints are unauthenticated and unthrottled. A trivial loop can exhaust CPU/bandwidth.

**Recommendation:**
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
```

### 3. PII disclosure on an unauthenticated endpoint (OWASP A01: Broken Access Control, A02: Cryptographic Failures)
`/users` returns email addresses with no authentication or authorization. Even with mock data today, this shape invites the same pattern to be extended with real data.

**Recommendation:** Require authentication and return only the fields the caller is entitled to.
```js
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const users = getUsers(); // from data layer
  res.json(users.map(u => ({ id: u.id, name: u.name }))); // omit email unless authorized
});
```
Where `requireAuth` validates a session/JWT and `req.user` drives authorization checks.

### 4. No CORS policy defined (OWASP A05)
Without an explicit CORS configuration, behavior is browser-default (same-origin), but this is easy to accidentally open up later. Make the intent explicit.

**Recommendation:**
```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend.example.com'], methods: ['GET'] }));
```

### 5. No global error handler / error leakage risk (OWASP A09: Logging & Monitoring Failures, A05)
Any thrown error will hit Express's default handler, which can leak stack traces when `NODE_ENV !== 'production'`.

**Recommendation:** Add a terminal error handler and ensure `NODE_ENV=production` in prod.
```js
